{
  "answer": "**In \"The Wanderer\" (chapter 11 of *Old English Elegies*), the opening lines state:** \"Often the lone-dweller awaits grace, / the Measurer's mercy, though he, heart-weary, / across the water-way long must / stir with his hands the rime-cold sea, / tread paths of exile. **Wyrd is wholly steadfast!**\"[^1]\n\nThis corresponds to the original Old English: *Wyrd bið ful aræd!* (lines 5), from paragraph [p-9cca5e] in the translation.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9cca5e).\n\n[^2]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" (original), [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/original/#p-9bd9cc).",
